1 (3) “Public record” has the meaning stated in [§ 4–101(j)] § 4–101 of the
2 General Provisions Article.
3 Article – Economic Development
4 TITLE 1.5. GENERAL PROVISIONS.
5 1.5–101.
6 (A) THIS TITLE APPLIES TO THE EMPLOYEES OF, CONTRACTORS WITH, AND
7 CONSULTANTS TO THE DEPARTMENT OR ANY OTHER ENTITY OR PROGRAM
8 GOVERNED BY THIS ARTICLE.
9 (B) NOTWITHSTANDING ANY OTHER PROVISION OF LAW, AN INDIVIDUAL
10 MAY NOT ENTER INTO A NONDISCLOSURE AGREEMENT WITH A PERSON INVOLVED
11 IN AN ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT ACTIVITY, INCLUDING A PERSON INVOLVED IN
12 ESTABLISHING OR OPERATING A DATA CENTER AS DEFINED IN § 11–239 OF THE TAX
13 – GENERAL ARTICLE.
14 Article – General Provisions
15 4–101.
16 (a) In this title the following words have the meanings indicated.
17 (b) “Applicant” means a person or governmental unit that asks to inspect a public
18 record.
19 (c) “Board” means the State Public Information Act Compliance Board.
20 (d) “Custodian” means:
21 (1) the official custodian; or
22 (2) any other authorized individual who has physical custody and control
23 of a public record.
24 (e) “INSTRUMENTALITY OF THE STATE” INCLUDES A PUBLIC SERVICE
25 COMPANY AS DEFINED IN § 1–101 OF THE PUBLIC UTILITIES ARTICLE.
26 (F) “News media” means:
27 (1) newspapers;

4 SENATE BILL 853
1 (2) magazines;
2 (3) journals;
3 (4) press associations;
4 (5) news agencies;
5 (6) wire services;
6 (7) radio;
7 (8) television; and
8 (9) any printed, photographic, mechanical, or electronic means of
9 disseminating news and information to the public.
10 [(f)] (G) “Official custodian” means an officer or employee of the State or of a
11 political subdivision who is responsible for keeping a public record, whether or not the
12 officer or employee has physical custody and control of the public record.
13 [(g)] (H) “Person in interest” means:
14 (1) a person or governmental unit that is the subject of a public record or a
15 designee of the person or governmental unit;
16 (2) if the person has a legal disability, the parent or legal representative of
17 the person; or
18 (3) as to requests for correction of certificates of death under § 5–310(d)(2)
19 of the Health – General Article, the spouse, adult child, parent, adult sibling, grandparent,
20 or guardian of the person of the deceased at the time of the deceased’s death.
21 [(h)] (I) (1) “Personal information” means information that identifies an
22 individual.
23 (2) Except as provided in § 4–355 of this title, “personal information”
24 includes an individual’s:
25 (i) name;
26 (ii) address;
27 (iii) e–mail address;
28 (iv) driver’s license number or any other identification number;

SENATE BILL 853 5
1 (v) medical or disability information;
2 (vi) photograph or computer–generated image;
3 (vii) Social Security number; and
4 (viii) telephone number.
5 (3) “Personal information” does not include an individual’s:
6 (i) driver’s status;
7 (ii) driving offenses;
8 (iii) five–digit zip code; or
9 (iv) information on vehicular accidents.
10 [(i)] (J) “Police officer” has the meaning stated in § 3–201 of the Public Safety
11 Article.
12 [(j)] (K) “Political subdivision” means:
13 (1) a county;
14 (2) a municipal corporation;
15 (3) an unincorporated town;
16 (4) a school district; or
17 (5) a special district.
18 [(k)] (L) (1) “Public record” means the original or any copy of any
19 documentary material that:
20 (i) is made by a unit or an instrumentality of the State or of a
21 political subdivision or received by the unit or instrumentality in connection with the
22 transaction of public business; and
23 (ii) is in any form, including:
24 1. a card;
25 2. a computerized record;
26 3. correspondence;

6 SENATE BILL 853
1 4. a drawing;
2 5. film or microfilm;
3 6. a form;
4 7. a map;
5 8. a photograph or photostat;
6 9. a recording; or
7 10. a tape.
8 (2) “Public record” includes a document that lists the salary of an employee
9 of a unit or an instrumentality of the State or of a political subdivision.
10 (3) “Public record” does not include:
11 (i) a digital photographic image or signature of an individual, or the
12 actual stored data of the image or signature, recorded by the Motor Vehicle Administration;
13 or
14 (ii) a record or any information submitted to the Public Access
15 Ombudsman or the Board under Subtitle 1B of this title.
16 [(l)] (M) “Technical infraction” means a minor rule violation by an individual
17 solely related to the enforcement of administrative rules that:
18 (1) does not involve an interaction between a member of the public and the
19 individual;
20 (2) does not relate to the individual’s investigative, enforcement, training,
21 supervision, or reporting responsibilities; and
22 (3) is not otherwise a matter of public concern.
23 4–103.
24 (a) All persons are entitled to have access to information about the affairs of
25 government and the official acts of public officials and employees.
26 (b) To carry out the right set forth in subsection (a) of this section, unless an
27 unwarranted invasion of the privacy of a person in interest would result, this title shall be
28 construed in favor of allowing inspection of a public record, with the least cost and least
29 delay to the person or governmental unit that requests the inspection.

